diff:1612462714:1612382085:=58,66d57%0a%3c #foxbegin 210204-181834-76080#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Structure and Grammar %0a%3c -> - BenP%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I think language structure has something to do with it. Cockney English and African American Vernacular both use the same structure, where adjectives go before the nouns they modify, and nouns come before the verbs for which they are the subject. I'm not sure about the other languages you mentioned but I'm guessing they use the same, or similar, structure. But if I use English vocabulary and pronunciation, but shuffle around the grammar, would I be using a different language or just speaking incorrect English?%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210204-181834-76080#%0a
